T*
(- Electricity should first be understood as a scientific principle before it is treated) Tj
T*
(as an exam topic.) Tj
T*
(- The learner must understand basic circuit ideas and electrical quantities because it) Tj
T*
(controls how questions in Electricity are answered correctly.) Tj
T*
(- A strong answer in Electricity uses the correct physical reasoning process and) Tj
T*
(explains why that method fits the task.) Tj
T*
(- Describing what happens in a simple series circuit is the type of application that) Tj
T*
(helps move the topic from explanation to mastery.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Step-By-Step Method) Tj
T*
(1. Read the question or example and identify the part connected to Electricity.) Tj
T*
(2. Recall the specific rule, process, or principle behind basic circuit ideas and) Tj
T*
(electrical quantities.) Tj
T*
(3. Apply the correct physical reasoning process step by step instead of jumping to the) Tj
T*
(answer.) Tj
T*
(4. Check the result carefully and confirm that it matches the requirement of the topic.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Worked Examples) Tj
T*
(Worked Example 1) Tj
T*
(1. Start with an example based on describing what happens in a simple series circuit.) Tj
T*
(2. Identify the exact idea in basic circuit ideas and electrical quantities that the) Tj
T*
(question is testing.) Tj
T*
(3. Apply the correct method for Electricity step by step without skipping reasoning.) Tj
T*
(4. Check the final answer and explain why it is correct.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Worked Example 2) Tj
T*
(1. Choose a second example that still focuses on current, voltage, and simple circuits.) Tj
T*
(2. Break the task into smaller parts and link each part to the rule being used.) Tj
T*
(3. Point out how to avoid thinking current gets used up in a circuit while solving it.) Tj
T*
(4. Review the result and connect it back to the topic overview.) Tj
